sentences: Lester Koenig (December 3, 1917 – November 20, 1977) was an American screenwriter, film producer, and founder of the jazz record label Contemporary Records.

In 1937, B.P. Schulberg offered him a job as a writer at Paramount Studios and he moved to Los Angeles.
In 1941, Koenig recorded Lu Watters which he followed on with Bob Scobey and Turk Murphy.

World War II interrupted his career and he served in the film unit of the United States Army Air Corps where he wrote the war documentary films, Memphis Belle: A Story of a Flying Fortress (1944) and Thunderbolt (1947), both directed by then-Major William Wyler.

Koenig had two children with Heerman, John (born 1950) and Victoria (born 1951).
